e for sexual and religious offences in the city states of Geneva and Venice. Technical terms have been cut to a minimum to ensure accessibility and appeal to lawyers, social, political and legal historians, undergraduate and postgraduates as well as general readers interested in the development of the trial through time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdministrative courtszEnglandxHistory. 0aAdministrative courtszEuropexHistory. 0aEcclesiastical courtszEnglandxHistory. 0aEcclesiastical courtszEuropexHistory. 0aTrialszEnglandxHistory. 0aTrialszEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aChurch courts.  aGiorgio Moreto.  aLaura Querini.  aPope Boniface VIII.  aamateur judges.  acivil litigation.  acivil trials.  acriminal trials.  aearly modern England.  aecclesiastical trials.  alate medieval England.  amanorial courts.  aprofessional judges.  aprosecution.  areligious offences.  aroyal courts.  asecular trials.  asexual offences.1 aDenton, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmholz, R. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaconelli, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlerman, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaven, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulholland, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulholland, Maureen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMusson, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaphy, William G., 